The Prague Stock Exchange finished with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected their losses.
Transactions of <0xC4><0x8C>EZ stocks reached about half of their value on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of Tuesday’s trade, reacted immediately to Monday’s fall when it went down to about 6%.
The decline this time is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
It is also here that the market reacts to the outcome of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives that refused to support the stabilization plan of the secretary of the financial sector.
Fall of stocks in Asia
Shares of the Asian Stock Exchanges fell dramatically on Tuesday, although over the course of the day the index finally attenuated some of the losses.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng stock index over its financial day marked nearly four percent, although it later mitigated its losses by reducing the decline by virtually 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movements of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the Index secretary, fell to 3.6 percent.
“The rescue actions planned in the U.S. are unsafe and this affects the financial market around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, that is, without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong’s interest rates are at the same level as those of the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should meet again as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that the falls will be felt in other countries.
The Bloody Bath of American Actions
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the plan to help the financial system, which should be allocated $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner).
Lawmakers, in that way, ignored President George Bush’s invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would solve the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks suffered a bloody bath and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell to almost seven percent, with a similar volume drop last recorded in 1987.
The index went down before it was announced, but as soon as it was shown that the assembly’s proposal did not go forward, the index began to fall freely.
Congress Withdraws: U.S. Government May Inject $700 Billion Into Bank
The top representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed on a pact in broad terms of financial aid to the American financial system.
The vote will take place at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers caused a gap in talks on the approval of the bailout plan in its form of aid to the U.S. financial system in the amount of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion kronor).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must fine-tune some details of the contract before they can make public the final form of the law and that it be voted on.
The financial aid plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the Committee on Financial Services and the Bank of the Assembly, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could be held in the Senate not before Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the bailout plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
After that, however, "disenchantment" will be achieved thanks to the complex mechanisms whose help to the market will also reach in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made a great breakthrough.
We resolve our discrepancies regarding how the package of measures should have to stabilize the market," Democrat Nancy Pelosi<0xC3><0xA1> told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still be held on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with finance minister Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give a definitive shape to the government fund.
It should buy unsold mortgage assets from financial corporations that lead to financial firms to heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are about to close the agreement on the plan, which will work and should also be effective in the market.
It is still necessary to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we are already in it," Paulson said.
A Sign for Asian Businesses
The global financial crisis has an explicit impact on the stock market that is rapidly declining.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are doing everything they can to get Congress to definitively pass a deal on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors in the Asian financial market as these are the ones in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday’s trade.
However, for now there is nothing clear for sure about when the two chambers of the American Congress will vote and, not even if they will not stall at the last minute with some problem.
Lawmakers believe it will be approved in the coming days.
The law, however, will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount destined to help the system should be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion have to be available as soon as possible, as President George Bush requested.
However, Congress could block the release of the remaining amount if it had the impression that the program did not fulfill its function, which would be another $100 billion and, later, the last $350 billion.
Bush applauded the progress of the meetings
On the other hand, the president can veto this decision, but Congress can outperform his veto by a majority vote.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program that consisted of earning financial resources for the repurchase of bad mortgage bonds whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to finish paying off their mortgages was retained.
“We have worked everything.
The House of Representatives would have to be ready to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday,” Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the meetings.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush is satisfied with Saturday’s advance and appreciates “the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy.”
Limitation of the Armored Contract
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said legislators decided on the program’s money responsibility for protecting taxpayers’ taxes from their losses, a relief clause of the planned financial plan.
The new law should also limit so-called armored contracts for directors of the participating companies of the program, and create a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This would have to be directed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on it, and we’ve made a big breakthrough towards the agreement that will work and that will be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes helping homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree to the new mortgage payments it buys in order to lower the monthly payments charges to debtors’ deadlines and enable them to stay with their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but quite difficult.
“And that’s why it’s not known with what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for the distribution of losses between the financial sector and the government,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not so relevant, according to Marek.
“Much more importantly, this week the congressmen agree on their support and give them their good looks as soon as possible.
“This important and psychological agreement that that approval is reached is, at the moment, the most important thing,” Marek said.
Armed Hand Struggle: The MP3 Player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
What seems clear is that it is better to buy only the phone.
Still, there are enough reasons for man to acquire only the breeder.
The choice depends practically on the manner of its use and the requirement of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for him to acquire the most modern record to listen to Maxim Turbolenc’s latest album.
On the other hand, this type of music products such as LPs no longer come out, and in terms of their quality there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If you stick vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues music on your shelves, you’re probably dreaming, at least, of this type of record.
This is the same with the music that is on the way, that is, the compressed, simplified music - the music in MP3.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as well as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the twenty-crown market helmets.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life
Some of the best players get so much more than just playing music and even that which not even most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Faced with the most basic functions such as calling, sending messages, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera and even manage to navigate.
And when we consider the Smartphone and the PDAs will also have a small computer in their pocket.
This is a small miracle as no refrigerator knows how to grill and no TV can photograph.
The universality of mobile phones also brings us disadvantages.
The more features you use on the mobile before the display indicator will light up asking to be recharged.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy tragedies.
Few are mobile phones that can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) clearly have higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that inexpensive mobile phones will not play more than two hours.
If in addition to this, above, constantly call get even, for more safety, a charger for the job - this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem will not have, as even the worst ones last at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile phone.
Unfortunately only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only in some unreduced drives can connect the small memory cards that are used on mobile phones.
On the players, with some exception (iPod), no special software is required.
Simply fill the device with music through the computer's USB.
Most mobile phones and players create their own order in the music library according to the performer's name, album title, genre or user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Search and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a particular equipment be interested in the strength of the accumulator, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to music as a background and you will listen to it every day only for a while, as in the tram, then you are enough with any mobile that you play.
This is what virtually any mobile device can do.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or the player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and virtually all the music that comes to it will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and with the exception of it the absolute majority of devices play music in WMA format.
The smaller ones include the AAC format (the format used by Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough through the mobile internet to visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or album.
This service could by itself be a weighty argument to purchase a mobile for music.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is miserable and the majority is limited only to the issues of fleeting success of the radios.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (either by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always wear a mobile phone.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you’ll find the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least hands-free ones.
If not, you can use a built-in player that has virtually every mobile even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobiles with music will be its price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns can already acquire a good walkman.
To most of you will limit the absence of an entry for classic headphones.
The best, even in terms of the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing more than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - really handles them anyone.
The minimal functions, their handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the playable discs is obvious.
It does not pose a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, gigantic account by downloading data.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest phones (e.g., the Vodafone 527) usually have a memory card change slot (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card will reach the two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
Basic models are usually only equipped with a 2 GB card of maximum capacity.
Only the most expensive ones have 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (up to 2 GB) no more than 1,100 kroner need to be spent.
If you are considered one of the most demanding music lovers, you can use the most specialized mobile-walkers (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of a single player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles of the walkman line have almost identical use as that of an independent MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over 4,000 crowns, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and accumulator (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the most cited brand brings MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
- Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It probably won't be long before we get there.
That the Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobil.cz.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) also confirmed that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the European Commission’s latest steps in the field of regulation of roaming fees it is likely to come to a paradoxical situation – for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if they are sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, said that there is no longer room in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find any frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in prices to which classical operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both here and there.
It has been shown that there is room for these types of operators and that they can be successful.
For the rest, it is not necessary to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we inform you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, are often contrasted with the offer of more tailored services.
For example, Tesco mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half of them cheap compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a rather trivial target group.
This operator is specifically aimed at the man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and who he can be trusted with,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept like that of Poland could stick in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small to be accessed by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it doesn’t seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokesman for the financial group Penta, told mobile.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do their best to avoid any potential competition.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only landline but also mobile phone services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have been able to move forward in the meetings,” said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times will shine.
It seems that, according to unofficial information, the first official operator would probably have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesperson for Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, in exceptional accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
“On the T-Mobile network, it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied in such a short period of time."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of spending and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, which would lead to a drop in prices and thus a drop in profits.
So why facilitate entry to the competition?
When the operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:phone emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile society.
This is confirmed by the public information available on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds: “Furthermore, not too long ago the competitive environment in the mobile market was open to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail great requirements for him and, above all, for his services.
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This is purely owned by the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of the potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for the classical operators," added Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, and they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally, we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile telephony services"
Of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market means and the fall in prices do not fall within the interest of OHSU.
The really dramatic shock in all of this is in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
“The Office has not found any signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in accountability in their market performance.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecom regulators," Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is, of course, an analysis of relevant markets drawn up by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech traders has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer a different view - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are strikingly ascending similarly.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including GTS Novera) show that many similar obstacles are encountered in all negotiations with operators.
Carrying responsibility in the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications of which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have met with him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently tabled to extend the competence of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of commercial tenders that was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this perfectly, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when no one's looking
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator that already exists in Czech mobile networks remains unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile telephony services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large amount of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resales.
“If cases such as those mentioned could be discovered we could talk about a breach of the contract conditions that could translate into the end of the collaboration with the given society,” Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity carried out by mobile operators would reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make nothing less than negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible as a percentage of customers.
They must also accept that their phone’s SIM card is not in their name, so they can’t absolutely dispose of it as a normal operator’s customer.”
This is exactly what it should look like to the <0xC4><0x8C>TU at least strange.
There is also a new question for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If it is the mobile operators that surround the eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their trading conditions do not allow it.
When will we cease to be the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this eruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical – too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the more advanced countries, however, regulators have intervened at this time and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to make the first virtual operator appear and with it began to appear more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority all this case passes as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the attributes in these cases suits them.
But we will not despair.
If this information is right behind the scenes and the virtual operator actually gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile market is likely to start moving again.
If any of the carriers let in any virtual mobile operator it will be difficult for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
