Talking Sleeping
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up very sluggish telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they’re asleep.
The first time it happens, you probably get scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somniloquios.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one person has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines their appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (sleeping) or sleepwalking, but they don’t have to be.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or over-excitement.
It is an unstudied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a whisper or the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him a way out.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress disorder).
What you can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to bed.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and find it very difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the somnolence appears try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful Advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very anxious during several episodes you should consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If he understands what he says (which is not the usual thing), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him for information.
You will not achieve anything, because when you are asleep you are not aware of how to organize your thinking.
Moreover, you will hear what it says, but you do not know what it is dreaming to say that, with great care in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not bad, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
