The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence that had been seriously hampered by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, in February 1994 the Government of Canada conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not happen again.
While Judge Krever was late to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, nearly 38 per cent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Décary.
The situation was disheartening.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” he says before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in what followed in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that " trust is something extremely fragile " .
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease characterized by brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, we instituted exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow donors to detect the presence of the virus directly in the blood rather than antibody against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors become infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means we’ll have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product to occur.
I think that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worry,” says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, for example, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You have to be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary said before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec should also provide for a sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Because anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
Aging of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average brings together only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria, can still donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria occurs, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covered the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
But members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it’s hard to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since today’s life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating their blood,” Francine Décary laments.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bench our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this " , since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
