Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice President and Director of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world’s largest gold company attempted a <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 million defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate”.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation persecution, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, and the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly arrangement that will dampen the opposition as well as scare anyone who will dare to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by bluffing.
It was therefore enough for the miner to open her books, her files and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for Noir Canada’s authors.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a “public” debate by disregarding the views of this one?
According to the Vice President, this word seems to refer only to high-paying lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand — or doesn’t want to understand — is that the public that supports Noir Canada’s authors and publishers does so mainly because it rejects the brutal manner of mining.
This public is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes of arguments, and not in the context of what many people perceive as a persecution-bittery (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a demand with respect to the authors of Noir Canada rather than intimidating them).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold trial is a direct attack on the freedom of university search and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and debate facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that dislike the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he claims, he does not want to make a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
