Psychology of Overlapping: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have discovered the neurological - economic - basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers was playing the lottery, the other was participating in an auction and while the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI).
In both games participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called strata located below the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the nervous system’s “self-premium” mechanism.
Thus, according to the scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the group members even lost that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the victory was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than members of the control group and the "winner" group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York's Faculty of Economics.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around the world some five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; they are characteristic of liver infection and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and with body humor (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
It is recommended for travelers to protect themselves by vaccine against viruses A and B, there are no vaccines against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After this, jaundice appears on the skin and on the whites of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last as long as two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people die in the world from cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical check-up, is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
Currently, there are about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory checkup as well, it is worth consulting with your family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to the results of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also eased the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
As part of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and to the same number of atheists, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University are also involved.
The analysis was carried out as follows; they attached a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the patient, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a 17th-century work by Sassoferrato and the Lady of the Arminian by Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary show would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a soothing effect.
The patients spent half an hour on an MRI scan, receiving in that period 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics asserted that by looking at the Virgin Mary they felt “safe” as “protected” people, “reassured themselves and peace reigned in their hearts.”
When they looked at the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality,” Wright added.
After these formidable results, one question remains: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of her size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary have even better results?
