Intelligent car mimics the flight of the bee
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the existing obstacles sensors in nature?
For example, the bees.
In a surprising project presented at Japan’s CEATEC, the bees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C robotic vehicle steering system, which was given the characteristics of the bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each bee creates its own oval private space that actually looks a lot like our protective security capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, chief technology officer of RP and development and research.
Composite eyes of bees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor that is immediately transformed into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot mimicking the movements of the bees, modifying the direction by rotating the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any current system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should be carried out in one open and close the eyes.
However, unlike bees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
Thus, instead of the endless possibilities that exist for bees to avoid other bees, here only rotary movement and acceleration in addition to braking were used as a possibility for the robot of the car.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process data, let alone the storage.
This apparatus in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No gigabytes or megabytes are required.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan’s calculations can be incorporated into series-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination, avoiding existing obstacles in their way.
