A written version of the $700 billion bailout bill has been prepared to be implemented in several phases in order to buy bad loans from banks.
In the first phase, half of the money will be spent.
According to the East Coast timetable during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion financial bailout package in total, after several days of discussion, Reuters reported.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the U.S. Congress, stating that it is only necessary to formalize the agreement in a document.
The commitment on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise, said: This program will work and be efficient, but more action is needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the economy around.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 a.m. on Monday morning, according to Central Europe time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock market.
On the bill called the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, first Monday will vote in the U.S. Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy low-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion will be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum, the Ministry of Finance will buy stocks of credit, bad grade and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
This program will be controlled by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion will be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and credit-fund securities, plus other “poisonous” credits as well.
The purchase can be made at auction or in direct form - competent people of the ministry reported.
The law allows the affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson asserted that the law thus secures the necessary financial means, which can reach as much as $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it be the purchase of bad financial means, its insurance or the prevention of risks that could lead to the collapse of some major financial institutions.
“We will do everything we need to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it,” he added.
On the other hand, the heads of banks that are in trouble and waiting for state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensations, which the U.S. argot simply calls gold parachutes.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, furthermore, the limitations depend on the form of assistance of the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachute, unless the bank's failed boss is retired.
By buying bad credits directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that bosses’ compensation is not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations apply only to new contracts to thus also stimulate participation in the programme.
This is the first case in U.S. history that a legal limitation will be in place for directors-general revenues, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional committee responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the participating banks in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they can ultimately even make profits from the transaction as soon as the economy and the bank recovers.
Under the bill, in the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to repay taxpayers the losses of the financial sector.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed their reservations about the project.
“This is not what the American citizens ordered us, that is, taxpayer dollars are not being protected,” said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
Her fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur, said the moves were pushed by those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007's prices, the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 percent compared to those in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 percent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose only to a minimal extent, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industries rose minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to the month of July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to a 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The highest price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemicals production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a price drop in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing houses and printing houses did not change.
In the rest of the sectors of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, there was an increase of 13.2 per cent, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a drop in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year, prices in the processing industry globally increased by 10.2 percent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices outpaced the previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, with prices in the energy sector and intermediate sectors unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In the production of consumer goods, there was a decline of 6.8 percent and in investment goods by 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 per cent against the euro and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
