We must also re-examine the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are widely effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the large use of portable musical instruments and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that it causes.
"Scientists confirm that this is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine, together with Member States and stakeholders, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from noise exposure from portable musical instruments and soap operas."
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but concern increases as hearing damage can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and exposure time to noise.
In its opinion, the Scientific Committee of the European Union points out that if users of portable musical instruments listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours per week they exceed the currently in force limit for the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods, risk permanent hearing loss after a period of 5 years.
