Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historic halls
The historic cinemas close favoring the multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the major Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of the marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the monkey rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear almost always are historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, a friend with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago I always won the Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay the most are mainly the halls of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas less, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for its disappearance is the event of the multiplex, are own of these three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new meticone cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, “it would be useful if new structures were built, but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its attendees are willing to move to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year.”
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to worry about the closures, decided to repair the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala be in the historical center and on the outskirts.
Among the rules envisaged are mediation of tax facilitation in favour of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special parking fees.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” notes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope other cities will follow the example of Bologna setting up other measures.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of meticons, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Cinema Paradise", which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
